    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1943-07-16T04:35:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1943-07-16T04:35:00-05:00" n="622"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d622">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">891.516/171: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Iran</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Dreyfus</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Tehran</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1943-07-16T13:00:00+03:25"
                            >July 16, 1943—1 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received July 17—10:54 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>727. Department’s 226, May 7.<note n="99" xml:id="d622fn99">Not printed: it
                        transmitted a message from the Federal Reserve Bank of New York to the
                        Banque Mellie Iran (891.516/165a).</note> Millspaugh and Director of Banque
                    Mellie request Department to endeavor to arrange for the conversion into gold
                    and shipment to Iran by air of one million dollars <pb facs="0596" n="584"
                        xml:id="pg_584"/> of Iranian Government deposit in Guaranty Trust Company
                    terms and conditions to be similar to those of previous shipment. Cable reply
                    requested.</p>
                <p>For the Department’s information British sales of gold in Iran are proceeding
                    sucessfully. Daily sales are limited to 8,000 sovereigns although there is
                    demand for more. Rate today is 550 rials per sovereign. Since present British
                    stock of 100,000 sovereigns will soon be exhausted additional 200,000 are being
                    brought from Cairo. Bazaar reports point to steadying of prices, perhaps partly
                    as result of gold sales. Bar gold imported by Iranian Government from United
                    States is being minted into gold pahlevis for sale under similar conditions as
                    British coins.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Dreyfus</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
